# Check Figma variables (`/check-variables`)

When asked to check variables, audit **Figma design tokens / CSS variables** (not JS runtime variables) against **semantic role**: each token must match how the element is used in the UI.

## 1. Clarify the target

State whether the input is a **page**, **component**, or **other UI** (section, pattern, etc.) before listing issues.

## 2. Read the UI holistically

Before judging individual tokens, note structure and hierarchy:

- Page background
- Surface fills (cards, panels, inputs, chips, etc.)
- Borders (dividers, outlines, hairlines)
- Text colors (primary, secondary, muted, links, errors)
- Icon colors
- Secondary / tertiary nested UI

## 3. Verify each token in context

For every styled element, the **variable role** must match the **element role**:

| Token kind   | Used on                          |
| ------------ | -------------------------------- |
| Surface      | Filled areas, backgrounds, wells |
| Border       | Strokes, outlines, dividers      |
| Text         | Typography color only           |
| Icon         | SVG / icon glyph color          |

Flag **misapplication** (e.g. text token on a surface fill, icon token on body copy, surface token on a border).

## 4. Output format

- **One line per issue** (file + element or selector + what’s wrong + what role it should use).
- If nothing is wrong:

`All variables applied correctly.`

### Example issue lines

```text
src/pages/Dashboard.tsx — card container uses `--color-text-primary` as background; use a surface token.
src/components/Button.tsx — border uses `--color-icon-muted`; use a border token.
```

Do not bundle multiple problems into one paragraph; keep each issue a single scannable line.
